Machine Learning for Acoustics Summer School 2019¶

- UKAN Network, Gregynog Hall, Wales (UK) -¶

Summary of Challenge¶

This is my solution to the final challenge that was proposed at the end the one week long Machine Learning for Acoustics Summer School organized by UKAN Network in Gregynog Hall https://acoustics.ac.uk/early-careers-group/acoustics-network-summer-school-2019/. Although I didn't get the right answer at the end of the challenge, my team and I were pretty close..if we just had 5 more minutes!! Luckily foosball was there to channel our frustration. Anyway, the train journey back to Scotland was long enough (and slowed down by bad weather) to have time to fix the code and polish it. Here's a summary of the challenge and below you can find the full solution.

Goal of the challenge:¶

The goal of the challenge was to apply machine learning techinques learned during the week to a problem in acoustics. Specifically, this was a problem related to NDT (non destructive testing) of a composite plate. NDT uses ultrasounds to detect cracks or damages in structures such as a bridge, a building, a composite plate. A change in the response to ultrasounds can raise an alarm on the state of the structure. A training set was first given to the participants to obtain a model of the undamaged plate. After a couple of hours, a validation data set was provided to test the validity of the model. Finally, during the last our of the challenge, an evaluation data set was sent to the participants. This evaluation data set consisted just of 50 points and the aim of the challenge was to predict how many -and possibly which- of these points were damaged.

Techiques used:¶

Unsupervised Learning, Features Extraction, Fast Fourier Transform, Density Estimation, Radial Basis Function Kernel, Nonlinear Regression, Classification

Language:¶

Python.

A crash course on Python for Data Science was provided during the week. Main libraries used: Numpy, Scipy, Matplotlib, Panda. The machine learning techniques were coded by hand, in order to better understand the theory, hence no machine learning libraries were used.

Output:¶

The official solution provided at the end of the challenge reported that all the points in the evaluation data set were damaged points. Of course, it also depends on the threshold used to classify a damage point. The threshold should answer the question: how far from the density of the other points in the model a point should be in order to be classified as damaged? Initially my answer reported in this solution was ~23 points. However, I was able to tweack the model and tune the hyperparameters and obtain the sought result of 49 damaged points. Here are six figures that summarize this results. The full solution is reported below.

</table></tr>

The figure on the left represents the feature extraction related to resonance frequency. For each point, a fast Fourier transform of its response to the ultrasonic signal was computed. The frequency of the maximum of the fft at each point was calculated and is plotted on the left. We can clearly see two distributions that correspond to the first and second modes (see full solution for details). These two frequencies can be computed by looking at the figure on the right, which is the resonance frequency density distribution of the training data obtained with a 1D RBF kernel.

</table></tr>

A 2D RBF kernel density distribution can provide a better model to identify the system. The two features plotted in these two graphs are resoance frequency and maximum amplitude at resonance. On the left, the training points are plotted on top of their calculated distribution. On the right, the evaluation set is plotted on top of the training points density distribution. It is already evident that many of the evaluation data are abnormal, but it is hard to quantify how many. So for now an estimate can be given by visual inspection.

</table></tr>

Finally, a "density score' is calculated by training the model on training and validation data sets, while testing on all the data. The - log of the density of the data is plotted for each point of a data set which is the concatenation of training, validation and evaluation data sets. The last 50 points corresponds to the evaluation data set, and show a very high novelty score. It is possible to calculate how many points are abnormal by fixing a threshold, e.g. density score = 5. For every point having a density score higher than 5, their coordinates are retrieved and plotted on the graph on the right. A more detailed discussion on the results is provided at the end of the full solution.

</table></tr>

Final Challenge - Full Solution¶

We want to create a machine learning model that is capable of detecting whether a recorded ultrasound signal in a structure is indicative of damage or any other change in the structure.

Experiment Information:

  • Ultrasonic waves were generated in a thin carbon fibre composite plate
  • Plate was excited with 5μs width square pulse transmitted through a piezo-electric transducer
  • Recorded out of plane surface velocity of plate with scanning Polytech laser vibrometer
  • Scanned at random locations distributed across a 300mm x 300mm CFRP plate
  • 100 averages recorded at each location to reduce noise
  • Recording triggered with external trigger from waveform generator

  • Bursts recorded at 1 MHz sample rate, with 4μs recorded after trigger + 10% pre-trigger (0.4μs), making signal 4096 samples in length

    Data Provided:

  • Wave data files consist of two variables:
    • "wave" - an $n \times d$ matrix where n are the number of ultrasonic pulses collected and d is the number of data points in each wave
    • "xyz" - $n \times d$ matrix with number of observations along the rows and , x,y,z coordinates along the columns

Challenge steps:

  • 1) Training: You will load and visualise the training data, extract features from it and train and cross-validate a model

  • 2) Validation: You will be given more data to validate your trained model

  • 3) Evaluation: We will "place" a small number of sensors on known locations, and evauate a set of waveforms and decide whether an alarm should be raised or not

Step 2: Features Extraction¶

Then I started to plot some features that could give some insight on the data. For example, the main features I looked at for each point were:

  • the maximum absolute amplitude of vibration
  • the rms
  • the frequency spectrum of the vibration to retrieve the resonances
  • the maximum amplitude of a point's resonance

All these features are important to create a model that describes the plate system. If the model is good enough, in case the plate will get cracked overtime, the new measurements will fall outside the model and highlight the broken parts of the plate.

Feature 3: Resonance Frequencies¶










In [456]:



    


## Feature 3 and 4: extract resonance frequncies of the signals and max amplitude at the resonances

# Import some library useful for fft
import scipy as sy
import scipy.fftpack as syfp
import pylab as pyl

# Initialize a fft matrix with same dimensions as the training set
X_train_shape = np.shape(X_train)
fft_X_train = np.zeros(X_train_shape)

# Fill each row of the FFT matrix with a Fast Fourier Transform of each signal in X_train
for iRow in range(X_train_shape[0]):
    fft_X_train[iRow] = syfp.fft(X_train[iRow, :])

# Sample Rate as provided in the challenge text (1 MHz)
SR = 1*10**6

# Length of the original signals
N = X_train_shape[1]

# Avoid aliasing by multiplying sampling frequency by 1/2 and form frequency vector
f = np.linspace(0, 0.5*SR, N)

# Plot frequency spectrum against amplitude for each point in the data set
plt.figure()
plt.ylabel("Amplitude")
plt.xlabel("Frequency [Hz]")
plt.plot(f[:N // 2], np.abs(fft_X_train)[:N // 2])
plt.title("Frequency Spectrum of Training Set")

# Assign the value of the fft to a temporary matrix
fft_temp = np.abs(fft_X_train[:,:N // 2])
fft_temp_shape = np.shape(fft_temp)

# Feature 3: max amplitude in the frequency spectrum for each point
fft_feature_amp = np.zeros(fft_temp_shape[0])

# Feature 4: index corresponding to the max amplitude, i.e. resonance frequency of every point
fft_feature_index = np.zeros(fft_temp_shape[0])

# For every point in the training set, calculate the frequency which has the maximum amplitude (fft_feature_index)
# and its amplitude (fft_feature_ampliude)
for i in range(fft_temp_shape[0]):
    fft_feature_amp[i] = np.max(np.abs(fft_temp[i,:]))
    fft_feature_index[i] = np.multiply(np.divide(np.argmax(np.abs(fft_temp[i,:])), fft_temp_shape[1]), SR/2)

# Plot the maximum frequency of vibration of every point
plt.figure()
plt.plot(xyz_train[:,0], fft_feature_index, 'o')
plt.title('Resonance frequency at every point')
plt.xlabel('x coordinates')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
#plt.savefig('FrequencyDistribution.png')

# Plot the amplitude of each max frequency 
plt.figure()
plt.plot(xyz_train[:,0], fft_feature_amp, 'o')
plt.title('Max Amplitude of spectrum at every point')
plt.xlabel('x coordinates')
plt.ylabel('Amplitude')

# Plot the maximum frequency of every point in a contour plot
plt.figure()
plt.tricontourf(xyz_train[:,0], xyz_train[:,1], fft_feature_index,20)
plt.title('Resonance Frequency Contour Plot')
plt.xlabel('x coordinates')
plt.ylabel('y coordinates')
plt.colorbar(shrink = 0.8)
print('')

Some considerations on these features.


    

  • amplitude and rms: they show that the plate vibrates above all in the middle and along the middle axis
    • 

  • frequency: the last plot shows two main frequencies of vibration, the lowest one. (~90 kHZ) is the first mode of vibration, which is expected to be in the middle of the plate according to plates theory. The second mode is usually higher (here ~240kHz) and is an antiphase vibration of two opposite parts of the plate.
    • 



We have now higlighted the behaviour of the points in the plate in terms of amplitude and frequency of vibration. When the new measured data will arrive in the evaluation set, we expect that if, for example, one of the new points is in the middle of the plate and resonates at a different frequency from the one highlighted here (~90 kHz) the point in that plate might be corrupted / cracked. This is a usual behaviour in structures: a crack in a plate, bridge or building will change its resonance frequencies and affect its vibration in general, including the maximum amplitude.


But we'll think about this later, now it's time to train a model that uses these features to describe the system under test.


Step 3: Training¶












We choose an unsupervsed approach, to learn the density distribution of each feature. First, using a RBF Kernel we obtain the density of just one featureat a time (1D RBF Kernel Density Estimation).


Then we use a 2D RBF Kernel to obtain the Density Estimation of two features sets: eg max amplitude and rms, or resonance frequency and amplitude at that frequency.













Kernel Density RBF Function¶
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radial_basis_function_kernel











In [457]:



    


# Import necessary libraries
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist

## Kernel Density RBF Function Definition
def kernel_density_rbf(x_train,x_test, h):
    r = cdist(x_train,x_test,'sqeuclidean')
    K = np.exp( -r/h )
    density = (1/h)*np.mean(K, axis=0)
    return density

X_val_shape = np.shape(X_validation)
fft_X_val = np.zeros(X_val_shape)

# Fill each row of the FFT matrix with a Fast Fourier Transform of each signal in X_train
for iRow in range(X_val_shape[0]):
    fft_X_val[iRow] = syfp.fft(X_validation[iRow, :])

# Sample Rate as provided in the challenge text (1 MHz)
SR_val = 1*10**6

# Length of the original signals
N_val = X_val_shape[1]

# Avoid aliasing by multiplying sampling frequency by 1/2 and form frequency vector
f_val = np.linspace(0, 0.5*SR_val, N_val)

# Plot frequency spectrum against amplitude for each point in the data set
plt.figure()
plt.ylabel("Amplitude")
plt.xlabel("Frequency [Hz]")
plt.plot(f_val[:N // 2], np.abs(fft_X_val)[:N // 2])
plt.title("Frequency Spectrum of Validation Set")

# Assign the value of the fft to a temporary matrix
fft_temp_val = np.abs(fft_X_val[:,:N // 2])
fft_temp_shape_val = np.shape(fft_temp_val)

# Feature 3: max amplitude in the frequency spectrum for each point
fft_feature_amp_val = np.zeros(fft_temp_shape_val[0])

# Feature 4: index corresponding to the max amplitude, i.e. resonance frequency of every point
fft_feature_index_val = np.zeros(fft_temp_shape_val[0])

# For every point in the training set, calculate the frequency which has the maximum amplitude (fft_feature_index)
# and its amplitude (fft_feature_ampliude)
for i in range(fft_temp_shape_val[0]):
    fft_feature_amp_val[i] = np.max(np.abs(fft_temp_val[i,:]))
    fft_feature_index_val[i] = np.multiply(np.divide(np.argmax(np.abs(fft_temp_val[i,:])), fft_temp_shape_val[1]), SR_val/2)

# Plot the maximum frequency of vibration of every point
plt.figure()

Step 6: Discussion and Conclusion¶












1) It is important to study the dataset, to give an initial check and know what we are dealing with
2) Extracting the right features is important, so in this case being an acoustician helped. A similar task, though, can be obtained by using deep learning, but it would make it more difficult to interpret the results.
3) We identified the system correctly using the trianing set, but when using more data (training + validation) we could retrieve more damaged points. So..more data is always better
4) Some decisions had to be made arbitrarily:



- the classifier threshold
- tuning the hyperparameter to choose the best model fit
- Although we could add more machine learning techniques to manage these parameter, I think that to check and interpret our final conclusions a knowledge of acoustics is required, which leads to the final point.



4) Final insight: in this case an answer was provided, so when I obtained a model that gave me 50 abnormal points I was happy. In real life though, nobody will tell us what the solution of a problem really is. In this case, the only way to really verify that our points are damaged is to be sure that we have identified meaninguful features that change due to a crack. I guess that my point is, humans are still needed - for now - and they'd better know acoustics!
